INSERT INTO `woodd_posts` VALUES('22', '1', '2013-11-22 19:59:52', '2013-11-22 19:59:52', '<p>The Loop</p><p>Languages: English • Français • Italiano • 日本語 • Português do Brasil • Русский • 中文(简体) • 中文(繁體) • (Add your language)</p><p>Contents</p><p>[hide]</p><p>1 Using The Loop</p><p>2 Loop Examples</p><p>2.1 Style Posts From Some Category Differently</p><p>2.2 Exclude Posts From Some Category</p><p>3 Multiple Loops</p><p>3.1 Loop Examples</p><p>3.1.1 Multiple Loops Example 1</p><p>3.1.2 Multiple Loops Example 2</p><p>3.2 Multiple Loops in Action</p><p>4 Nested Loops</p><p>5 Sources</p><p>6 Resources</p><p>7 Related</p><p>7.1 More About The Loop</p><p>7.2 Articles</p><p>7.3 Code Documentation</p><p>The Loop is PHP code used by WordPress to display posts. Using The Loop, WordPress processes each post to be displayed on the current page, and formats it according to how it matches specified criteria within The Loop tags. Any HTML or PHP code in the Loop will be processed on each post.</p><p>When WordPress documentation says &quot;This tag must be within The Loop&quot;, such as for specific Template Tag or plugins, the tag will be repeated for each post. For example, The Loop displays the following information by default for each post:</p><p>Title (the_title())</p><p>Time (the_time())</p><p>Categories (the_category()).</p><p>You can display other information about each post using the appropriate Template Tags or (for advanced users) by accessing the $post variable, which is set with the current post\'s information while The Loop is running.</p><p>For a beginner\'s look at The Loop, see The Loop in Action.</p><p>via <a href=\'http://codex.wordpress.org/The_Loop\'>The Loop « WordPress Codex</a>.</p>', 'The Codex', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'the-loop-wordpress-codex', '', '', '2013-11-22 19:59:52', '2013-11-22 19:59:52', '', '0', 'http://localhost/woodd/?p=22', '0', 'post', '', '0');
